# ===========================================
# COMPANION PLATFORM - Environment Variables
# ===========================================

# Server Configuration
COMPANION_PORT=3020
COMPANION_BIND_HOST=0.0.0.0
# COMPANION_HOST is the *public* hostname/port Companion reports in its own
# startup logs (src/index.ts) — it does NOT drive brand resolution or OAuth
# redirect_uri generation; each brand's own `companionUrl` (base registry,
# registry.ts) is the source of truth for that (see CLAUDE.md's "Gotchas").
# A plain localhost value is fine here for local dev.
COMPANION_HOST=localhost:3020
COMPANION_PROTOCOL=http
COMPANION_SECRET=your-secret-at-least-16-chars

# Local dev note: brands are resolved by matching the inbound `Host` header
# against a brand's (code-only, non-overridable) `companionHosts` — for edo
# that's the real prod/stage hostnames (registry.ts), which won't match
# anything on your machine. For local dev against edo, set `BRAND_FORCE=edo`
# below (bypasses Host matching entirely) rather than trying to get a local
# hostname into `companionHosts`.

# File storage
COMPANION_FILE_PATH=/tmp/

# Health check key (gates the detailed /api/brands view)
HEALTH_CHECK_KEY=your-secret-health-check-key

# Redis (shared state across replicas: readiness checks, express-session's
# OAuth-handshake store, the whoami response cache + circuit breaker
# (src/modules/auth/session-resolver.ts, whoami-breaker.ts), and the
# rate-limit counters below). In production this is provided by Railway's
# Redis plugin — do not set it by hand there. Defaults to a local dev
# instance if omitted.
# REDIS_URL=redis://localhost:6379

# Rate limiting (express-rate-limit + rate-limit-redis, Redis-backed so the
# counter is shared across replicas). Two independent limiters:
#   - RATE_LIMIT_* : per brand+user/IP, mounted only on /uppy and /api/*.
#   - RATE_LIMIT_GLOBAL_* : per-IP, mounted globally BEFORE express-session/
#     attachUser so it also bounds `/`, OAuth, `/s3`, and `/api/brands` — the
#     whoami fetch attachUser triggers is otherwise unprotected by the
#     per-route limiter alone (security review MEDIO-1). Exempts
#     /api/healthz and /api/readyz (polled continuously by the orchestrator).
# RATE_LIMIT_WINDOW_MS=60000
# RATE_LIMIT_MAX=300
# RATE_LIMIT_GLOBAL_WINDOW_MS=60000
# RATE_LIMIT_GLOBAL_MAX=600

# ===========================================
# BRAND SELECTION & OVERRIDE (src/modules/brand/{registry,identity,detect}.ts)
# ===========================================
# Brands are declared in CODE (src/modules/brand/registry.ts), one deep-frozen
# entry per known slug (abe, picaboo, edo). At runtime a brand is resolved as:
#   1. the code-only base registry entry
#   2. + <SLUG>_BRAND_OVERRIDE (below) — auth string fields only
#   3. + per-brand secrets (see "PER-BRAND SECRETS" further down)
# There is no COMPANION_BRANDS CSV and no per-brand JSON config blob anymore
# (both are retired — see the bottom of this file). Requests are routed to a
# brand by matching the inbound Host header against that brand's
# `companionHosts` (code-only, NOT settable here) — see detect.ts.
#
# Only `edo` is servable today (registry.ts — `abe`/`picaboo` have no
# confirmed external whoami endpoint yet, so their `companionHosts` is
# intentionally empty and they get no Companion instance).

# BRAND_FORCE routes EVERY request to one slug regardless of the Host header.
# Use it for a single-brand local dev shell, or a dedicated deploy pinned to
# one brand/apex. Must name a SERVABLE slug — the server fails to boot
# otherwise (assertBrandForceIsServable, detect.ts).
# BRAND_FORCE=edo

# <SLUG>_BRAND_OVERRIDE (JSON) merges over the base registry's `auth` object.
# ONLY these string fields may be overridden: whoamiUrl, signInUrl,
# signOutUrl, sessionCookieName. Anything else (kind, whoamiAllowedHosts,
# assets.s3Prefix, companionHosts, s3, providers, ...) is code-only and is
# silently dropped (with a logger.warn) if present — this is a deliberate
# SSRF/tenant-isolation boundary (identity.ts), not an oversight. A
# malformed/non-JSON value fails SILENTLY back to the base config (no log) —
# run `npx tsx scripts/verify-brand-config.ts` after editing this to confirm
# it took effect.
#
# IMPORTANT: designer/node-socket (in the abeduls3 monorepo) and this
# Companion MUST be pointed at the SAME whoami/sign-in endpoints for a given
# environment — set the SAME EDO_BRAND_OVERRIDE value (or the equivalent
# override each of those services reads) everywhere, or a user could pass
# auth on one service and fail on another purely from environment drift.
#
# Example: point edo at STAGE instead of the production URLs baked into the
# base registry (registry.ts's edo entry is production by default):
# EDO_BRAND_OVERRIDE={"auth":{"whoamiUrl":"https://edonext-app.stage.entourageyearbooks.com/api/user","signInUrl":"https://edonext.stage.entourageyearbooks.com/login","signOutUrl":"https://edonext-app.stage.entourageyearbooks.com/logout","sessionCookieName":"auth_session_stage"}}
#
# Note: `companionHosts` already lists BOTH the prod and stage Companion
# hosts in the base registry (registry.ts) — since companionHosts itself
# can't be overridden, stage and prod share one registry entry and are told
# apart only by which whoamiUrl this override points at.

# ===========================================
# PER-BRAND SECRETS (Fase 6 — src/lib/secrets.ts#loadBrandSecrets)
# ===========================================
#
# SECRETS_SOURCE selects HOW every brand's S3 credentials + OAuth provider
# secrets are loaded (brand-independent switch; default "env"):
SECRETS_SOURCE=env
# SECRETS_SOURCE=aws

# --- SECRETS_SOURCE=env (default) ---
# Plain process env vars, one set per brand, keyed by an env-var PREFIX
# derived from the brand slug: uppercase it and replace "-" with "_"
# (e.g. slug "edo" -> prefix "EDO"). IN PRODUCTION these are Railway
# *service variables* configured per-service in the Railway dashboard — they
# are never committed and never live in a shared .env file on the server.
#
# S3 (bucket/region fall back to the code-only base registry when unset;
# access/secret key are REQUIRED under SECRETS_SOURCE=env — Railway has no
# instance IAM role to fall back to — UNLESS the global AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID/
# AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY fallback below is set):
# <PREFIX>_S3_ACCESS_KEY=AKIA...
# <PREFIX>_S3_SECRET_KEY=...
# <PREFIX>_S3_BUCKET=...
# <PREFIX>_S3_REGION=us-east-1
# <PREFIX>_S3_ACCELERATE_ENDPOINT=false
#
# Example for the "edo" brand:
# EDO_S3_ACCESS_KEY=AKIA...
# EDO_S3_SECRET_KEY=...
# EDO_S3_BUCKET=entourage-uploads
# EDO_S3_REGION=us-east-1
#
# Global fallback (src/lib/secrets.ts#readEnvBrandSecrets): if a brand has no
# <PREFIX>_S3_ACCESS_KEY/<PREFIX>_S3_SECRET_KEY of its own, these two are used
# instead — shared across every brand under SECRETS_SOURCE=env. There is NO
# such fallback for bucket/region (each brand's <PREFIX>_S3_BUCKET/_REGION,
# or the base registry, is authoritative for those). Also used directly by
# `src/lib/aws/s3Client.ts` as the ultimate fallback when no explicit
# access/secret key reaches it at all.
# AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID=your-access-key
# AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=your-secret-key
# AWS_REGION=us-east-1
#
# OAuth providers (all optional; a provider is only wired once BOTH _KEY and
# _SECRET are set for it):
# <PREFIX>_DROPBOX_KEY / <PREFIX>_DROPBOX_SECRET
# <PREFIX>_FACEBOOK_KEY / <PREFIX>_FACEBOOK_SECRET
# <PREFIX>_INSTAGRAM_KEY / <PREFIX>_INSTAGRAM_SECRET
# <PREFIX>_ONEDRIVE_KEY / <PREFIX>_ONEDRIVE_SECRET
# <PREFIX>_BOX_KEY / <PREFIX>_BOX_SECRET
# <PREFIX>_UNSPLASH_KEY / <PREFIX>_UNSPLASH_SECRET
# <PREFIX>_ZOOM_KEY / <PREFIX>_ZOOM_SECRET
#
# Google (wired once <PREFIX>_GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID is set; the rest are optional):
# <PREFIX>_GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID=....apps.googleusercontent.com
# <PREFIX>_GOOGLE_CLIENT_SECRET=GOCSPX-...   # classic OAuth flows only
# <PREFIX>_GOOGLE_DRIVE_API_KEY=AIzaSy...    # Drive Picker
# <PREFIX>_GOOGLE_PHOTOS_API_KEY=AIzaSy...   # Photos Picker
# <PREFIX>_GOOGLE_APP_ID=...
#
# --- SECRETS_SOURCE=aws (optional) ---
# Reads one JSON secret per brand from AWS Secrets Manager instead of plain
# env vars. `@aws-sdk/client-secrets-manager` is loaded via a dynamic
# import() and is NEVER pulled in under the default SECRETS_SOURCE=env.
# SECRETS_MANAGER_REGION=us-east-1        # falls back to AWS_REGION, then us-east-1
# <PREFIX>_SECRETS_ID=companion/edo       # falls back to "companion/<slug>"
#
# The secret's SecretString must be JSON shaped like:
# {
#   "s3": {
#     "accessKey": "AKIA...", "secretKey": "...",
#     "bucket": "...", "region": "us-east-1", "useAccelerateEndpoint": false
#   },
#   "providers": {
#     "google": { "clientId": "...", "clientSecret": "...", "driveApiKey": "...", "photosApiKey": "...", "appId": "..." },
#     "dropbox": { "key": "...", "secret": "..." }
#     // ...facebook / instagram / onedrive / box / unsplash / zoom, same {key, secret} shape
#   }
# }
# Every field is optional; a missing bucket/region falls back to the
# code-only base registry, same as the env source. Unlike the env source,
# missing S3 credentials are NOT a fail-fast error under aws — the AWS SDK's
# Default Credential Provider Chain (IAM role) applies. The whole cache is
# warmed ONCE at process boot (top-level await in secrets.ts) before the
# brand registry is built.

# ===========================================
# RETIRED — do not use (kept only as a pointer for anyone finding old docs)
# ===========================================
# The abeduls3-alignment cutover (2026-07, see docs/superpowers/plans/2026-07-
# 02-companion-multibrand-alineacion-abeduls3.md) removed, with NO
# compatibility layer, everything that used to live in this section:
#   - COMPANION_BRANDS (CSV brand list) and the "first brand = default brand"
#     concept — brands are now resolved by Host (see "BRAND SELECTION &
#     OVERRIDE" above), not by an ordered CSV.
#   - One big per-brand JSON blob env var (e.g. `ABEDULS='{...}'`,
#     `<SLUG_UPPER_SNAKE>`) with fields like `rootDomain`, `auth.url`,
#     `auth.cookieName`, `public.backendUrl/uploadUrl/loginUrl`,
#     `corsOrigins`, `uploadUrls`, `enabledPlugins` (CSV) — replaced by the
#     code-only base registry (registry.ts) + `<SLUG>_BRAND_OVERRIDE` (auth
#     fields only) + `upload.plugins` (typed array) + per-brand secrets (see
#     above).
#   - Global, unprefixed OAuth/S3 env vars (`COMPANION_DROPBOX_KEY`,
#     `COMPANION_GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID`, `AWS_BUCKET_NAME`,
#     `COMPANION_AWS_ACCELERATE_ENDPOINT`,
#     `COMPANION_ENABLE_GOOGLE_PICKER_ENDPOINT`, `DEFAULT_AUTH_URL`, ...) —
#     replaced by the per-brand `<PREFIX>_*` scheme above (`AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID`/
#     `AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY`/`AWS_REGION` are the one exception that's still
#     read, as a cross-brand fallback — see "PER-BRAND SECRETS" above).
#   - The `abeduls.local` cookie-domain-matching local dev flow and its
#     `rootDomain`/`public.loginUrl` cross-origin cookie contract — auth is
#     now the `partner-whoami` flow (CLAUDE.md's "session-resolver.ts"),
#     which forwards whatever cookie the browser sends Companion to the
#     brand's `whoamiUrl`, instead of Companion validating a shared
#     `Domain=.<rootDomain>` cookie itself.
# See CLAUDE.md's "Brand resolution & config" section and `git log` on this
# file for the full old shape if you need archaeology.